phase2.explanation:
Files.readAllLines() throws IOException if the file doesn't exist!

Unlike the old File.exists() approach, NIO's Files utility throws exceptions for failures.

FIX: Check if file exists first:
if (Files.exists(path)) {
    List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(path);
    // process lines
} else {
    System.out.println("File doesn't exist!");
}

Or catch the exception and handle it appropriately.

NIO is more fail-fast — it doesn't silently fail like the old File class.

phase3.solution:
import java.nio.file.*;
import java.io.*;
import java.util.List;

public class NIOPractice {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            Path path = Paths.get("data.txt");

            // Write content
            String content = "Line 1: Hello\nLine 2: World\nLine 3: NIO is great!\n";
            Files.write(path, content.getBytes());
            System.out.println("File written!");

            // Check if exists
            System.out.println("Exists: " + Files.exists(path));

            // File size
            System.out.println("Size: " + Files.size(path) + " bytes");

            // Read and print lines
            List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(path);
            System.out.println("Content:");
            for (String line : lines) {
                System.out.println(line);
            }

            // Delete
            Files.delete(path);
            System.out.println("File deleted!");

        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
